"That would be downright robbery, Tony," said Aunt Katy, assuming the pathetic;
                  "and I know you wouldn't go and treat her as fed and clothed you like a mother
                  that way, indeed, Tony."

"You'll give me a glass, Tony, sure? I never meant a morsel of harm, but joking;
                  and I'll get the trembles and die without the brandy, Tony. You'll let me have a
                  stiff drink, and Judy shall go back."

"But, Charlotte, we know that the alcohol itself leaves the system very rapidly;
                  now, why not suppose that it carries with it a portion of the disease, of the
                     malaria, if we may call it so, of the system?"

"It is remarkable that all the diseases arising from drinking spirituous or
                  fermented liquors are liable to become hereditary, even to the third generation;
                  increasing, if the cause be continued, till the family becomes extinct."—Darwin.
